Integrative Analysis using MFA (v2. using 5 data sets after expansion)

Alex Sánchez-Pla and Ferran Briansó

2022-05-23

Introduction

Files exclusive.matrix.genes.Rda and exclusive.matrix.prots.Rda contain expression values from genes and proteins selected for being differentially expressed from a TCGA breast cancer dataset, plus (in additional rows) the new features coming from the respective annotation processes already performed with annotate_and_expand script. File intersect.matrix.Rda contains only new features coming from the biological annotations in common between both data sources.

Breast cancer subtypes

Source [https://www.breastcancer.org/types/molecular-subtypes#section-luminal-a-breast-cancer]

Triple-negative or basal-like breast cancer is estrogen receptor-negative, progesterone receptor-negative, and HER2-negative. Triple-negative breast cancer is considered more aggressive than either luminal A or luminal B breast cancer.

HER2-enriched breast cancer is estrogen receptor-negative and progesterone receptor-negative and HER2-positive. HER2-enriched cancers tend to grow faster than luminal cancers and can have a worse prognosis, but are usually successfully treated with targeted therapy medicines aimed at the HER2 protein.

Luminal A breast cancer is estrogen receptor-positive and progesterone receptor-positive, HER2-negative, and has low levels of the protein Ki-67, which helps control how fast cancer cells grow. Luminal A cancers tend grow more slowly than other cancers, be lower grade, and have a good prognosis.

Data loading

The loaded matrices contain numeric values for either genes, proteins or a set of new variables (GO or similar annotations) derived from the selected annotations from each data set or the intersection between them.

## [1] 0

## [1] 0

## [1] 0

## [1] 0
#colnames(annotCommon)

numSamples <- ncol(annotGenes)
numGenes <- nrow(matGenes)
numProts <- nrow(matProts)
numGOsInGenes <- nrow(annotGenes)
numGOsInProts <- nrow(annotProts)
numGOsInCommon <- nrow(annotCommon)

There are:

  • 150 samples,
  • 200 genes,
  • 3 annotation-derived features in the exclusive annotations from gene matrix,
  • 111 proteins,
  • 51 annotation-derived features in the exclusive annotations from prots matrix,
  • 10 annotation-derived features from the intersect annotations from both sources.

Preparing MFA

While the application of MFA is that of an exploratory analysis, so that there is no unique approach the list provided by Husson et Josse (2010) is a useful “checklist” to organize the analysis:

  1. Define the structure of the data (groups of variables and/or individuals)
  2. Define groups of active and supplementary variables
  3. Scale or not the variables
  4. Perform MFA
  5. Choose the number of dimensions to interpret
  6. Simultaneously interpret the individuals and variables graphs
  7. Study the groups of variables
  8. Study the partial representations
  9. Use indicators to enrich the interpretation

In order to apply MFA we need a unique matrix with obtained by merging all datasets through its common dimension, which is set to be “rows”, transposing the original matrices.

onlyGenes <- t(matGenes)#[,1:numGenes]
onlyProts <- t(matProts)#[,1:numProts]

jointBasicData <- cbind(onlyGenes, 
                        onlyProts)
jointBasicDataScaled <- cbind(scale(onlyGenes), 
                              scale(onlyProts))
dplyr::glimpse(jointBasicData)
##  num [1:150, 1:311] 4.36 1.98 1.73 4.36 2.45 ...
##  - attr(*, "dimnames")=List of 2
##   ..$ : chr [1:150] "A0FJ" "A13E" "A0G0" "A0SX" ...
##   ..$ : chr [1:311] "RTN2" "NDRG2" "CCDC113" "FAM63A" ...
jointExpandedData <- cbind(onlyGenes, 
                           onlyProts,
                           t(annotGenes),
                           t(annotProts),
                           t(annotCommon))
jointExpandedDataScaled <- cbind(scale(onlyGenes), 
                                 scale(onlyProts),
                                 scale(t(annotGenes)),
                                 scale(t(annotProts)),
                                 scale(t(annotCommon))
                                 )
dplyr::glimpse(jointExpandedData)
##  num [1:150, 1:375] 4.36 1.98 1.73 4.36 2.45 ...
##  - attr(*, "dimnames")=List of 2
##   ..$ : chr [1:150] "A0FJ" "A13E" "A0G0" "A0SX" ...
##   ..$ : chr [1:375] "RTN2" "NDRG2" "CCDC113" "FAM63A" ...

Each group is given a name and it may be given a data type and a color.

basicNames <- names(grupsBasic) <- c("genes", "prots")
expandedNames <- names(grupsExpanded) <- c("genes", "prots", "geneAnots", "protAnots", "commonAnots")
basicTypes <- c("c", "c")
expandedTypes <-c(rep("c", 5))
basicPalette <- c("red", "blue")
basicPalette2 <- c("black","red", "blue")
expandedPalette <- c("gray", "red", "blue", "orange", "cyan")

Defining active/suplementary data

Variables describing biological knowledge are linear combinations of one or more omics variable types so it seems reasonable to start considering these as supplementary.

Supplementary groups are described by the index of the group in the vector that defines how many variables in each groups.

supplGroups <- c(3,4,5)

Scaling the variables

A quick check at the numerical part of the dataset can suggest if the data needs to be centered/scaled.

boxplot(jointBasicData, col=basicPalette, cex.axis=0.6, las=2)

boxplot(jointBasicDataScaled, col=basicPalette, cex.axis=0.6, las=2)

boxplot(jointExpandedData, col=expandedPalette, cex.axis=0.5, las=2)

boxplot(jointExpandedDataScaled, col=expandedPalette, cex.axis=0.6, las=2)

Applying MFA to basic data

MFA is applied on the “basic” matrix formed only by expressions, that has been previously scaled.

library(FactoMineR)
res.mfa.b <- MFA (base=jointBasicDataScaled, 
                      group=grupsBasic, 
                      name.group = names(grupsBasic),
                      type=basicTypes,
                      graph=FALSE)
dimdesc(res.mfa.b)

Representation of Groups

plot(res.mfa.b,choix="group", palette=basicPalette)

Study of individuals and variables

plot(res.mfa.b, choix="var",
     #invisible="quanti.sup",
     hab="group",
     lab.var=TRUE, lim.cos2.var = 0.6, 
     palette=basicPalette2)

plot(res.mfa.b,choix="ind",partial="all",habillage="group",palette=basicPalette2)
## Warning: ggrepel: 135 unlabeled data points (too many overlaps). Consider
## increasing max.overlaps

plot(res.mfa.b,choix="axes",habillage="group",palette=basicPalette2)

Indivuals analysis with factoextra

Habillage parameter sets the phenotypes (= cancer subtypes)

library(factoextra)
## Welcome! Want to learn more? See two factoextra-related books at https://goo.gl/ve3WBa
# Variables
#fviz_mfa_var(res.mfa.b, palette = ...)

# Individuals
basicPalette3 <- c("coral", "green", "skyblue")
fviz_mfa_ind(res.mfa.b, habillage = brca.subtype, palette = basicPalette3) # color by groups

# Individuals with all vars
expandedPalette2 <- c("coral", "red", "green", "skyblue", "blue")
fviz_mfa(res.mfa.b, habillage = brca.subtype, palette =  expandedPalette2)# color by groups

Applying MFA to expanded data

MFA is applied on the “expanded” matrix formed by expressions and annotations, that has been previously scaled.

library(FactoMineR)
res.mfa.x<- MFA (base=jointExpandedDataScaled, 
                      group=grupsExpanded, 
                      name.group = names(grupsExpanded),
                      type=expandedTypes,
                      num.group.sup = supplGroups, graph=FALSE)
dimdesc(res.mfa.x)

Representation of Groups

plot(res.mfa.x,choix="group", palette=expandedPalette)

Study of individuals and variables

plot(res.mfa.x, choix="var",
     #invisible="quanti.sup",
     hab="group",
     lab.var=TRUE, lim.cos2.var = 0.6, 
     palette=expandedPalette)

plot(res.mfa.x,choix="ind",partial="all",habillage="group",palette=basicPalette2)
